---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import LikeButton from '../components/LikeButton.astro';
export const prerender = true;
---

<Layout
  title="Builder Inclusions & Selection Options"
  description="Complete guide to builder inclusions — structural upgrades, internal finishes, air conditioning, flooring, hot water, and external features for a new build."
>
  <LikeButton slug="inclusions" />

  <div class="inc">

    <!-- Breadcrumb -->
    <div class="breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a> &rsaquo; <span>Inclusions &amp; Options</span> &rsaquo; <span>Inclusions</span>
    </div>

    <!-- Page header -->
    <div class="inc-header">
      <h1>Builder Inclusions &amp; Selection Options</h1>
      <p class="inc-lead">A practical guide to what your builder includes by default — and what upgrades are worth negotiating before you sign.</p>
      <div class="inc-meta">
        <span>12 topics</span>
        <span class="sep">·</span>
        <span>Last updated 4 April 2026</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Intro -->
    <div class="intro-box">
      <p>All builders offer varying degrees of inclusions. Some offer packages costing $25–100k on top, but you can't get credit for items in those packages you don't want. Go through what inclusions you want first, price them individually with the builder, then decide if their package is actually worthwhile.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Key Takeaways -->
    <div class="takeaways">
      <div class="takeaways-title">Key Takeaways</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Price inclusions individually before comparing a builder's package.</strong> Packages can add $25–100k and you get no credit for items you don't want — knowing the individual prices first is the only way to tell if the package is actually worth it.</li>
        <li><strong>The slab pour is the real deadline, not plan sign-off.</strong> Recessed bathroom floors and flush stacker doors must be specified before the concrete is poured — but you can still request them after your plans are approved. Most people assume finalised plans means no more changes. The actual cutoff is slab day.</li>
        <li><strong>If you raise ceiling heights, raise door and window heights at the same time.</strong> Going to 2.74m ceilings with standard 2040mm doors looks wrong and costs more to fix later. Raise doors to 2340mm and align window header heights as one coordinated decision.</li>
        <li><strong>Ducted A/C has a hidden price jump at 4 zones.</strong> On an Actron Classic, zones 3 and 4 cost $350–500 each. Zone 5 isn't another $350–500 — it requires a full system upgrade at $4–8k before you add any zones. Decide how many zones you need before committing to a system.</li>
        <li><strong>A heat pump hot water system can eliminate your gas bill entirely.</strong> It already runs cheaper than gas. Add induction cooking and use reverse-cycle A/C for heating and you have no gas usage at all — no connection fee, no meter rental, no bill.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Section quick-nav -->
    <!-- Table of Contents -->
    <nav class="toc-card" id="page-toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
      <div class="toc-card-head">
        <span class="toc-card-title">Contents</span>
        <button class="toc-toggle" aria-expanded="true">[hide]</button>
      </div>
      <div class="toc-body" id="toc-body">
        <div class="toc-group">
          <div class="toc-group-label">Structural</div>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="#ceiling-height">Ceiling Height</a></li>
            <li><a href="#roof">Roof</a></li>
            <li><a href="#doors">Doors</a></li>
            <li><a href="#framing">Framing</a></li>
            <li><a href="#recessed-wet-areas">Recessed Wet Areas</a></li>
            <li><a href="#stacker-doors">Stacker Doors</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="toc-group">
          <div class="toc-group-label">Internal</div>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="#air-conditioning">Air Conditioning</a></li>
            <li><a href="#flooring">Flooring</a></li>
            <li><a href="#electrical">Electrical</a></li>
            <li><a href="#square-set">Square Set &amp; Skirting</a></li>
            <li><a href="#soundproofing">Soundproofing</a></li>
            <li><a href="#laundry-chute">Laundry Chute</a></li>
            <li><a href="#solar">Solar</a></li>
            <li><a href="#hot-water">Hot Water</a></li>
            <li><a href="#coffered-ceilings">Coffered Ceilings</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="toc-group">
          <div class="toc-group-label">External &amp; Other</div>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="#external">External Extras</a></li>
            <li><a href="#dog-door">Dog Door</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="toc-group">
          <div class="toc-group-label">Checklist</div>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="#checklist">Builder's checklist reference</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </nav>

    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
         STRUCTURAL UPGRADES
    ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <section id="structural">
      <div class="section-label">Structural Upgrades</div>

      <!-- Ceiling Height -->
      <div class="card" id="ceiling-height">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Ceiling Height</h3>
          <span class="badge-cost">$5–9.5k per floor</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p>Standard heights are 2.4–2.55m. Upgrading to 2.74m is the most common choice and noticeably improves how a room feels. Going taller is possible but check CDC/DA limits (typically 8.5m from ground level to roof ridge).</p>

          <div class="box-tip">
            <strong>How to achieve higher ceilings without hitting council limits</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Lower the roof pitch to reduce the total building height</li>
              <li>Replace drop edge beams (DEB) with higher ceilings — the cost difference between them is marginal</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="box-info">
            When raising ceiling heights, also raise door heights to 2.34m and align window header heights where it makes sense.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Roof -->
      <div class="card" id="roof">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Roof</h3>
          <span class="badge-neutral">Personal preference</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p>Both options are widely used — choice comes down to look, pitch, and frame type. Your pitch may dictate which is even possible.</p>
          <div class="compare-2">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Colorbond</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/colorbond-roof.jpg" alt="Colorbond roof" loading="lazy"></figure>
              <ul>
                <li>Required for flat or low-pitch roofs</li>
                <li>Use Anticon foil-based insulation underneath</li>
                <li>Rain noise is debated — many owners report no issues</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Tiles</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/monier-roof-tile.png" alt="Monier roof tiles" loading="lazy"></figure>
              <ul>
                <li>Not suitable for flat roofs</li>
                <li>Heavier — steel frame may need structural changes (~$3.5k)</li>
                <li>Traditional look; some builders default to this</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Doors -->
      <div class="card" id="doors">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Doors</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p>Standard doors are 2040mm × 820mm. When upgrading ceiling height, raise door heights to 2340mm. Builders start with hollow core doors — solid doors cost significantly more but make a real difference to soundproofing.</p>
          <div class="door-grid">
            <div class="door-item">
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/barn-door.png" alt="Barn Door" loading="lazy"></figure>
              <div class="door-name">Barn Door</div>
            </div>
            <div class="door-item">
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/cavity-slider-door.jpg" alt="Cavity Slider Door" loading="lazy"></figure>
              <div class="door-name">Cavity Slider</div>
              <div class="door-note">Good where there's no room for a swing door</div>
            </div>
            <div class="door-item">
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/external-door.png" alt="External Door" loading="lazy"></figure>
              <div class="door-name">External Door</div>
              <div class="door-note">Consider swing direction and storm protection</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="box-info">Wheelchair access requires a minimum 850mm door width.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Framing -->
      <div class="card" id="framing">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Framing</h3>
          <span class="badge-neutral">Site-dependent</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p>Builders who use steel frame argue it's better; timber-frame builders argue the same. Mostly personal preference, though soil conditions and tiled roofs may influence the decision.</p>
          <a href="/steel-or-timber-frame/" class="read-more">Read full guide: Steel or Timber Frame →</a>
          <figure class="full-img">
            <img src="/images/inclusions/steel-vs-timber-frame.png" alt="Steel vs Timber Frame comparison" loading="lazy">
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Recessed Wet Areas -->
      <div class="card" id="recessed-wet-areas">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Recessed Flooring to Wet Areas</h3>
          <span class="badge-cost">Up to $1k (GF) · $1–2.8k per bathroom (FF)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p>Without a recess, tiles sit on top of the slab creating a step into the bathroom. A recessed pour at slab stage gives a flush finish — this decision cannot be made after the slab is poured.</p>
          <div class="box-warn">
            <strong>Upper floor shortcut to avoid:</strong> Some builders cut into the 300mm frame to save cost. This can cause creaking and waterproofing failure over time. Ask for a proper alternative and budget $1–2.8k per bathroom.
          </div>
          <figure class="full-img">
            <img src="/images/inclusions/recessed-floor-wet-area.png" alt="Recessed floor wet area diagram" loading="lazy">
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Recessed Stacker Doors -->
      <div class="card" id="stacker-doors">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Recessed Stacker Doors (Flush to Alfresco)</h3>
          <span class="badge-cost">$350–$900 per set</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p>Standard stacker doors sit on top of the slab leaving a visible lip. A recessed slab pour creates a flush indoor-to-alfresco transition — worth it if you're investing in outdoor entertaining.</p>
          <div class="compare-2">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Recessed (flush finish)</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/recessed-stacker-doors.png" alt="Recessed stacker doors" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Slab preparation detail</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/recessed-stacker-door-slab.png" alt="Recessed stacker door slab" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
          </div>
          <figure class="full-img">
            <img src="/images/inclusions/stacker-doors-on-slab-with-lip.png" alt="Stacker doors on slab with lip — no recess" loading="lazy">
            <figcaption>Without the recess — the lip is visible at the base of the door frame</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Related guide cards -->
      <div class="guide-cards">
        <a href="/brick-cladding-hebel-or-otherwise/" class="guide-card">
          <span class="gc-title">Brick, Cladding &amp; Hebel</span>
          <span class="gc-desc">Choosing your external wall material</span>
          <span class="gc-arrow">→</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/windows/" class="guide-card">
          <span class="gc-title">Windows</span>
          <span class="gc-desc">Glazing, sizing, and what to ask your builder</span>
          <span class="gc-arrow">→</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/steel-or-timber-frame/" class="guide-card">
          <span class="gc-title">Steel or Timber Frame</span>
          <span class="gc-desc">Pros, cons, and site condition factors</span>
          <span class="gc-arrow">→</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
         INTERNAL UPGRADES
    ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <section id="internal">
      <div class="section-label">Internal Upgrades</div>

      <!-- Air Conditioning -->
      <div class="card" id="air-conditioning">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Air Conditioning</h3>
          <span class="badge-cost">Up to $30k</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <div class="compare-2">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Split System</div>
              <ul>
                <li>Wall units in each room</li>
                <li>Lower upfront cost</li>
                <li>Can add rooms later</li>
                <li>No ductwork in ceiling</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Ducted</div>
              <ul>
                <li>Hidden in ceiling — cleaner look</li>
                <li>Multiple zones (Actron up to 8; MHI up to 10)</li>
                <li>Actron Classic standard: 2 zones. Adding zones: $350–500 each up to 4. Beyond 4 requires a $4–8k system upgrade</li>
                <li>Duct types: round, multi-directional, or linear slimline ($240–380 per outlet)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="duct-grid">
            <figure>
              <img src="/images/inclusions/ac-duct-multi-directional.jpg" alt="Multi-directional duct outlet" loading="lazy">
              <figcaption>Multi-directional</figcaption>
            </figure>
            <figure>
              <img src="/images/inclusions/ac-duct-round.jpg" alt="Round duct outlet" loading="lazy">
              <figcaption>Round</figcaption>
            </figure>
            <figure>
              <img src="/images/inclusions/ac-duct-linear.png" alt="Linear slimline duct outlet" loading="lazy">
              <figcaption>Linear slimline</figcaption>
            </figure>
          </div>

          <div class="box-tip">
            Have the A/C company model kW requirements for your specific home. Account for which zones run simultaneously — not just total square metres.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Flooring -->
      <div class="card" id="flooring">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Flooring</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <table class="data-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Type</th>
                <th>Typically included?</th>
                <th>What to know</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>300×300 tiles</strong></td>
                <td>Yes — GF living areas</td>
                <td>Upgrading to 600×600+ adds tiles + labour (up to $40/m² labour alone)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Carpet</strong></td>
                <td>Yes — bedrooms, upper floor</td>
                <td>Upgrade underlay to acoustic AAAC rated (4–6 stars) for better soundproofing</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Laminate</strong></td>
                <td>Upgrade (~$5–10k upstairs)</td>
                <td>Builder-supplied laminate is usually budget grade — you'll likely want to upgrade</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Hybrid / vinyl</strong></td>
                <td>Upgrade</td>
                <td>Best waterproofing option. Modern systems like QuickStep are excellent</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Floor-to-ceiling tiles</strong></td>
                <td>Upgrade</td>
                <td>Budget several thousand per large bathroom</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Floor levelling</strong></td>
                <td>As needed</td>
                <td>Even in a new build the slab may not be perfectly level — installer corrects this with self-levelling cement</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>

          <div class="box-warn">
            <strong>Doing flooring post-handover?</strong> Ask your builder to: tack-fix (not glue) skirting boards, and lay floors <em>before</em> kitchen cabinets so you avoid gaps that need scotia to cover later.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Electrical -->
      <div class="card" id="electrical">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Electrical</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <div class="cost-list">
            <div class="cost-row">
              <span class="cost-label">Downlights (installed)</span>
              <span class="cost-value">$120–140 each</span>
            </div>
            <div class="cost-row">
              <span class="cost-label">Downlights (provision only)</span>
              <span class="cost-value">$75 each</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="guide-cards" style="margin-top: 16px;">
            <a href="/electrical-plan-and-home-automation/" class="guide-card">
              <span class="gc-title">Electrical Plan &amp; Home Automation</span>
              <span class="gc-desc">Full guide to planning your electrical and smart home setup</span>
              <span class="gc-arrow">→</span>
            </a>
            <a href="/lighting-tips-and-ideas-for-a-new-home/" class="guide-card">
              <span class="gc-title">Lighting Tips &amp; Ideas</span>
              <span class="gc-desc">Placement, types, and what makes a real difference</span>
              <span class="gc-arrow">→</span>
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Square Set -->
      <div class="card" id="square-set">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Square Set Ceilings, Cornices &amp; Skirting</h3>
          <span class="badge-cost">Square set ~$2k · Windows $150–200 each</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p>Square set means walls meet the ceiling with no cornice — a contemporary look with no architraves. Standard skirting is 66mm; upgrading to 90mm+ suits a modern home. Square set windows also work well in bathrooms where architraves interfere with mirrors.</p>
          <div class="compare-2">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Cornice (upgraded style)</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/cornice-upgraded-style.png" alt="Upgraded cornice" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Square Set</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/square-set-ceiling.jpg" alt="Square set ceiling" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-2">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Standard 66mm skirting</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/skirting-66mm-standard.png" alt="Standard 66mm skirting" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">90mm skirting (recommended)</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/skirting-90mm.png" alt="90mm skirting" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-2">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Square set windows</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/square-set-windows.png" alt="Square set windows" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Architraves (standard)</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/architraves-around-window.png" alt="Standard architraves" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Soundproofing -->
      <div class="card" id="soundproofing">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Soundproofing</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <figure class="full-img" style="max-width: 420px;">
            <img src="/images/inclusions/bradford-insulation.png" alt="Bradford Insulation" loading="lazy">
            <figcaption>Bradford Insulation</figcaption>
          </figure>
          <div class="compare-2">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Between floors</div>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Soundscreen insulation:</strong> $2k–$6.5k</li>
                <li><strong>Hebel PowerFloors:</strong> $20–35k</li>
                <li><strong>Fyrchek/Sounchek:</strong> $3k–$7k (denser gyprock ceiling)</li>
                <li><strong>Sound isolation clips + furring channels:</strong> $1.8k per room</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Between rooms</div>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Soundscreen/Gold Batts:</strong> $2k–$5.5k</li>
                <li><strong>Fyrchek/Sounchek:</strong> $3.5k–$7k (10–16mm dense gyprock)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="/soundproofing/" class="read-more">Read full soundproofing guide →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Laundry Chute -->
      <div class="card" id="laundry-chute">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Laundry Chute</h3>
          <span class="badge-cost">~$2k</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <div class="side-by-side">
            <div>
              <p>For double storey homes — a chute from first floor to the laundry below. Check your floor plan layout first as it's not always feasible depending on room positioning.</p>
            </div>
            <figure>
              <img src="/images/inclusions/laundry-chute.png" alt="Laundry chute" loading="lazy" style="width: 110px; height: auto;">
            </figure>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Solar -->
      <div class="card" id="solar">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Solar</h3>
          <span class="badge-cost">Solar $6–25k · Tesla battery $16.5k</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p>Builder-offered solar is usually from an affiliate and rarely offers better pricing than the open market. Solar can be added after handover though you may have visible pipes on the exterior.</p>

          <div class="box-warn">
            <strong>Battery ROI reality check:</strong> A Tesla Powerwall takes 11–15 years to recover costs, with a 10-year warranty — meaning you may need to replace it before breaking even. Better suited for energy independence than pure savings.
          </div>

          <div class="box-tip">
            Claim government rebates and get independent quotes rather than using the builder's affiliated installer.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Hot Water -->
      <div class="card" id="hot-water">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Hot Water Systems</h3>
          <span class="badge-cost">Heat pump $2–6k</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <div class="hw-types">
            <div class="hw-type">
              <div class="hw-type-label">Instantaneous — Gas</div>
              <p>Can run an entire house. Common builder default for continuous hot water.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="hw-type">
              <div class="hw-type-label">Instantaneous — Electric</div>
              <p>Per wet area only — doesn't produce enough litres per minute to run a whole house. Not recommended as the primary system.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="recommended-flag">Recommended: Heat Pump Hot Water System</div>
          <p>Heat pump systems run cheaper than both gas and traditional electric tanks. A 270L+ tank heats in ~3.5 hours and can connect to solar for near-zero running costs.</p>

          <div class="compare-2">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Integrated heat pump</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/heat-pump-integrated.jpg" alt="Integrated heat pump" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Separate heat pump</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/heat-pump-separate.png" alt="Separate heat pump" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="box-tip">
            Top picks: <strong>Sanden</strong> and <strong>Reclaim</strong> — both use CO2 refrigerant (more efficient than R134a). Pair with induction cooking and reverse-cycle heating to eliminate your gas bill entirely.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Coffered Ceilings -->
      <div class="card" id="coffered-ceilings">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Coffered Ceilings</h3>
          <span class="badge-cost">$2–4k</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p>A dropped/recessed ceiling panel that adds visual character to a room. Many variations available — cost depends on size and level of detail.</p>
          <div class="compare-3">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">With detail</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/inclusions/coffered-ceiling-details.png" alt="Coffered ceiling with details" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Standard</div>
